state legislators met tuesday with four 
of 200 students on the seventh day of their sitin to protest 
conditions at east tennessee state university 
rep roscoe dixon chairman of the legislatures black caucus 
said three of the schools administrators and three of the student 
protesters agreed to meet to resolve the impasse 
the caucus met with four of the protesting students from the 
historically black school the students who began the sitin last 
wednesday said they are protesting dilapidated classrooms and 
dormitories 
i wouldnt allow my pet dog to live in the dormitories out 
there said sen john ford a member of the caucus 
ford said 60 million was added to the nashville schools 
operating budget a few years ago but essentially a lot of things 
have not been done 
its going to take a lot of time he said you cant tear 
down a dormitory in one day the process is slow and long 
some of the protesters have left the sitin periodically to 
attend classes 
the university has an enrollment of 3800 students 
