<TEXT>
a developer that illegally bulldozed more than 
1500 soilconserving mangrove trees to make way for a 
marinacondominium project could be fined up to 25000 per tree 
or 375 million officials said 
the mangroves which play a vital role in floridas rapidly 
disappearing wetlands occupied a 1700foot stretch along a 
drainage ditch next to dumfounding bay part of the intracoastal 
waterway north of miami 
this is probably the largest mangrove destruction case in dade 
county history said robert karafel a code enforcement officer 
for 17 years 
the bulldozing was discovered jan 25 after an anonymous tip to 
the metrodade department of environmental resources authorities 
said monday 
officials at glendale federal bank backers of the project do 
not deny the bulldozing and said they are trying to resolve the 
situation glendale is responsible for any penalty karafel said 
even though we dont believe some of the mangroves were 
significant to the ecosystem we recognize they were removed 
illegally said stanley price an attorney for the thrift its 
just an unfortunate event it really is 
one settlement under discussion would have glendale pay a fine 
reimburse the agency for administrative costs and plant 22680 
mangrove seedlings 
the mangroves which grow along salt water create land by 
trapping soil and provide a haven for sea life in its roots the 
trees are best known for their curly aboveground root system and 
grow to about 25 feet high 
in maybe 25 years you might see what was destroyed karafel 
said when you cut off that food source it has longstanding 
impact on the entire food chain in the bay 
the contractor ryan construction co of sessner had a permit 
to clear only 100 feet of mangroves the thrift said in all about 
1890 trees were destroyed including some buttonwoods inspectors 
said 
