<TEXT>
the largest organization of older americans 
says an illtimed cut in social security taxes could destroy 
confidence in the pension system and make it harder to reduce the 
federal deficit 
but unless government officials can significantly reduce the 
deficit a tax cut may be a good idea once social security 
surpluses are sufficient to cover benefits for 18 to 24 months the 
american association of retired persons said tuesday 
aarp and two smaller organizations of senior citizens agreed in 
testimony before the senate finance committee that the government 
must stop using surplus social security taxes to hide the size of 
the overall deficit 
the house ways and means committee took a step in that direction 
tuesday by recommending that social security revenues not be 
considered when the overall deficit is calculated 
the finance committee is considering a bill by sen daniel 
patrick moynihan dny that would reduce social security taxes 
for workers and employers so that surpluses could no longer be 
available to mask the deficit 
the current system creates the illusion that the social 
security surplus can be used to pay for general government 
expenditures said lawrence t smedley executive director of the 
national council of senior citizens in a word the current 
budget system is dishonest 
smedley said taxes could be cut once reserves are sufficient to 
cover 15 to 18 months of benefits which probably would not be 
before 1993 
martha mcsteen president of the national committee to preserve 
social security and medicare said that since the budget is 
unlikely to be balanced soon the other way to keep government from 
spending surplus social security taxes is to eliminate them with a 
tax cut 
its much like getting rid of the ice cream and doughnuts 
before you go on a diet she said you remove the temptation 
and force yourself to make tough decisions 
aarp director judith n brown told the finance committee that 
cutting social security taxes just when the system is building 
needed reserves could weaken public confidence and support but 
she said a tax cut may be advisable once the reserves are built up 
so social security revenues arent used to reduce the deficit 
she said that unless other taxes were raised or spending cut to 
make up for the 55 billion a year that moynihans bill would lose 
the overall deficit would rise further increasing government debt 
and slowing the economy 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan advised against cutting 
social security taxes or taking the system out of the budget 
the current structure of social security may not be 
appropriate in all circumstances he said but at present it 
is still the best option 
greenspan said proposals to cut taxes and take social security 
out of the deficit calculation could reduce pressure for real cuts 
in the deficit and increase the difficulty of providing for the 
needs of an aging population in a way that is equitable across 
generations 
greenspans contention that a social security tax cut might 
destabilize the economy conflicts with a new study by two former 
treasury department officials 
economists aldona robbins and gary robbins argue that over 10 
years moynihans tax cut would increase the gross national product 
by 346 billion create 930000 jobs and raise investment capital 
by 162 billion 
unless the social security system is changed the robbinses 
wrote 
todays average 30yearold worker who will retire in 2025 
could see his income taxes rise by 20 percent if the government is 
to meet its social security promises 
these higher taxes will be equivalent to a 7 percent 
reduction in his or her social security benefits what the 
government gives with one hand it will be taking away with the 
other 
the study was done for the institute for policy innovation a 
dallas research organization 
