<TEXT>
airliner brakes cant handle highenergy 
aborted takeoffs as they wear thin even though they meet federal 
certification standards the national transportation safety board 
says 
blaming inadequate certification by the federal aviation 
administration for the may 21 aborted takeoff of an american 
airlines dc10 at dallasfort worth airport the safety board 
called tuesday for airlines to reevaluate the capacity of their 
brakes when they begin to wear out 
board member jim burnett said the problem could be costly for 
the aviation industry because without new brake designs it might 
involve reducing the capacity of airliners the distance they could 
fly or the length of runways 
the american jetliner skidded more than 1000 feet off the end 
of the runway injuring eight of its 254 occupants the plane was 
too severely damaged to repair 
it was the first time the board had cited faa certification of 
an airliner model as the probable cause in a crash burnett said 
we have already lost an airliner and we face the real 
possibility of losing a planeful of people he said after the 
fourmember panel approved a series of recommendations to the faa 
and airlines for testing the capacity of brakes when they are worn 
the board raised doubts about faa certification and test 
procedures for all airliner brakes which it said may fail when 
planes abort takeoffs at high speed 
the dallas plane scheduled to fly to frankfurt west germany 
reached 178 miles per hour before the pilot reversed engine thrust 
and applied the brakes the brakes failed before the plane reached 
the end of the runway 
the ntsb also blamed the brake manufacturer loral in the 
aborted takeoff 
board members said brakes near their wear limit dont have the 
same margin of safety as new ones and the faa didnt consider that 
when it certified the brakes on the dc10 two decades ago 
airlines have about 3000 rejected takeoffs each year but most 
are executed at a low enough speed that braking power combined 
with reverse engine thrust is adequate to stop the plane without 
damage 
but an average of about four highpowered rejections result in 
accidents each year board members said 
investigators testified that only the newest brakes are adequate 
to safely stop an airliner that has to abort a takeoff near 
v1 the velocity at which the plane ordinarily must continue 
its take off the american plane was near that speed when a warning 
light and audible signal indicated a wingslat problem 
the signal proved to be false but the board did not fault the 
pilot for aborting the takeoff 
in a separate action the board recommended that the dc10s 
warning system on wing slat deployment be redesigned so it wont go 
off so late in the takeoff investigators said planes are easily 
able to fly even when slats are in the worst position while a 
highpowered aborted takeoff can be dangerous 
</TEXT>
