<TEXT>
serious criminal fraud is three times as 
likely to occur at a failed savings and loan than at an insolvent 
commercial bank according to a top regulator 
federal deposit insurance corp chairman l william seidman who 
also serves as head of a new sampl bailout agency the resolution 
trust corp said about 60 percent of the thrifts seized by the 
government over the past year have been victimized by serious 
criminal activity 
in commercial banks criminal fraud is present in 17 percent to 
20 percent of failures he told the house ways and means oversight 
subcommittee tuesday 
if you can think of a kind of fraud well be able to show you 
an example in the sampls he said 
however a justice department official warned the panel not to 
expect speedy recovery of taxpayers losses on thrifts even though 
the administration is spending 49 million this year on 202 fbi 
agents and 30 trial lawyers to go after embezzlers 
the investigation and prosecution of major financial 
institution fraud typically will require many months or 
years said mark m richard deputy assistant attorney general 
moreover much of the money is gone the value of assets 
involved in the fraud often has plummeted and the defendant may 
have squandered his or her own assets leaving little or nothing to 
recover he said 
