<TEXT>
a governmentendorsed report recommends an 
ambitious effort by food companies physicians and individuals to 
improve health by reducing fat and cholesterol in the national diet 
the result says the expert panel that produced the report 
would be a 20 percent reduction in coronary heart disease 
the american public should have a greater range of 
lowsaturated fatty acid lowfat and lowcholesterol food options 
available and they should have the information to establish 
hearthealthy eating patterns said james cleeman coordinator of 
the national cholesterol education program 
the ncep report endorsed by government agencies and 26 health 
and professional groups includes recommendations ranging from 
nutrient consumption to standardized food labeling to educational 
programs 
heart disease is the nations no 1 killer disease claiming the 
lives of about 500000 americans each year it is associated with 
high levels of cholesterol in the blood which clogs arteries 
the panel recommended a twopronged approach the first of which 
seeks to identify and treat people at high risk of heart disease 
with dietary therapy and possibly medication those people 
generally have blood cholesterol levels of more than 240 milligrams 
per deciliter 
but more than 60 percent of the disabilities and premature 
deaths associated with heart disease occur in millions of americans 
whose cholesterol levels are below that level the report said 
these people as well as all americans over age 2 would benefit 
from the second part of the strategy aimed at lowering cholesterol 
levels by promoting healthful food choices and making food lower in 
saturated fat and cholesterol more widely available 
of greatest importance in the diet the report said is 
saturated fat from animal and vegetable sources saturated fats are 
more important to overall blood cholesterol levels than the amount 
of cholesterol consumed 
claims that foods with no cholesterol are healthier are 
misleading because the food may contain high amounts of saturated 
fat said dr richard carleton head of the population panel of the 
national cholesterol education program 
he said no food is a magic bullet for lowering cholesterol 
and that eliminating a single food such as egg yolks which have a 
high cholesterol content is also not a solution 
the report calls on the food industry to promote label and 
distribute goodtasting safe foods lower in fat and cholesterol 
and high in complex carbohydrates including soluble fiber 
it says the government should expand and standardize food 
labeling requirements so consumers can have more information the 
food and drug administration is drafting new foodlabeling 
regulations and legislation is pending in congress 
other recommendations call on health professionals to advocate 
healthier diets for educational programs and continued nutrition 
research 
if the recommendations are heeded large numbers of americans 
will be at lower risk of coronary heart disease carleton said 
on nutrients the panel recommends the same intake averages as 
recommended by the american heart association and the national 
research council they include less than 10 percent of total 
calories from saturated fat an average of 30 percent of total 
calories or less from all fat and less than 300 milligrams of 
cholesterol per day 
the report was endorsed by the ncep coordinating committee 
which includes the department of health and human services the 
department of agriculture and other government agencies as well as 
professional groups such as the american medical association the 
american heart association and the american public health 
association 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

