<TEXT>
the us government is faltering as japan and 
other countries work to make their manufacturers competitive a 
congressional advisory agency said today 
american manufacturing has never been in more trouble than it 
is now the office of technology assessment said in a 231page 
report prepared for the senate banking committee 
the report rekindles a twodecadeold debate over industrial 
policy and the governments role in private enterprise with the 
agency clearly siding with those favoring greater federal 
participation 
with few exceptions the us government has been reluctant to 
adopt proactive policies to build competitiveness it said 
the time is ripe for reopening the question before industry 
is so weakened that national security is threatened 
agency advisers suggested establishing a civilian technology 
agency through the national institute of standards and technology 
unless us industry and government take coordinated and 
timely action there will be a longterm deterioration of our 
industrial strength and military security and an erosion of our 
economic health they said 
the report acknowledged that selective government support of key 
technologies or industries amounts to picking winners and that 
government bureaucrats often are illequipped to make such choices 
as an example it cited the hundreds of millions of dollars the 
nowdefunct synfuels corp spent in the early 1980s subsidizing 
coal and shalebased substitutes for oil and natural gas 
but it said joint japanese governmentindustry efforts have not 
always enjoyed success 
among the japanese failures cited were attempts at jumpstarting 
biotechnology development building a fifth generation of computers 
and erecting a civilian airliner industry 
the dominance of us civilian aircraft manufacturers in world 
markets can be attributed to governmentsupported research on 
airframe and engine technologies in the early part of the century 
the report said 
a lesson is that a crisis is a poor crucible for making such 
decisions it said the failure of the synfuels project can be 
traced largely to the atmosphere of crisis in which it was born 
the advisers also cited government support of agricultural 
technology development through land grant universities and 
cooperative extension services as being a key to the rapid 
productivity growth of american farms 
it is possible to take the best from the picking winners 
debate and develop institutions for government collaboration with 
manufacturers without becoming captive to them the report said 
the argument cannot and should not be resolved by counting up 
successes and failures any sustained effort will include some 
failures and some industries might succeed more in spite of 
government support than because of it 
