<TEXT>
a federal judge has ruled that transportation 
workers who join unions have the same right as nonmembers to 
refuse to pay dues that would be used to promote political or 
ideological causes they oppose 
the decision tuesday by us district judge paul v niemeyer 
will make it easier for union members to demand rebates on their 
dues said attorney milton l chappell of the national right to 
work legal defense fund 
most unions have taken the position in the past that any right 
to pay a reduced fee only applies to nonmembers said chappell 
who brought the case on behalf of a greenbelt woman who belongs to 
the transportation communications international union 
niemeyer said that for the union to use her dues for political 
or ideological reasons violated her first amendment rights and the 
federal railway labor act 
niemeyer issued the ruling under the railway labor act which 
governs only the transportation industries but it could set a 
precedent for courts ruling on similar demands by other workers 
unhappy with their unions political activities 
other court decisions have held that nonunion members working 
in a union shop where all workers must join the labor 
organization could reject union assessments for activities not 
directly related to contract negotiations grievance procedures or 
other central functions 
mitchell m kraus general counsel for the transportation 
communications international union said the ruling was 
disappointing but he could not say whether the union which 
represents 100000 employees would appeal 
to my knowledge this is the first ruling of its kind kraus 
said 
the case was brought on behalf of kathryn a kidwell an amtrak 
secretary she objected to her dues being used for purposes 
unrelated to collective bargaining but said she did not want to 
quit the union 
in his decision niemeyer said kidwell was faced with the 
dilemma of staying in the union and having her money used for 
causes she opposes or leaving and giving up her right to vote on 
the terms and conditions of her employment 
in short she is given the option of protecting free speech 
or of protecting her vote on the continuation or conditions of 
work but not both the judge said 
he ordered the union to give kidwell and others similarly 
situated the right to receive a reduction in dues 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

