<TEXT>
the us economy grew by 09 percent in the 
fourth quarter of 1989 faster than previously estimated but still 
the slowest pace in more than three years the government said 
today 
the commerce department said its revised estimate of 
octoberdecember growth means the gross national product the 
nations total output of goods and services rose 3 percent for 
all of 1989 
that was the slowest yearly advance since a 27 percent gain in 
1986 and followed a 44 percent increase in 1988 
the fourthquarter gain was stronger than the initial report 
last month of 05 percent growth but was still the lowest since a 
08 percent advance in the third quarter of 1986 
a consensus of economists had indicated in advance of the new 
report that fourthquarter growth would be lowered to 04 percent 
the improvement should ease fears the economy had entered a 
downturn at years end although there is considerable anxiety over 
the months ahead 
the department will make one more revision in the gnp the 
broadest measure of the nations economic health after more solid 
information is available next month 
a recession usually is defined as two consecutive quarterly 
declines in the gnp the last decline was a onequarter drop of 18 
percent in 1986 after which the economy resumed growth the last 
recession occurred in 198182 
since then the economic expansion has continued for 87 months 
and in november broke the peacetime growth record if it continues 
through october 1991 it will set a new overall record 
an inflation index tied to the gnp rose 45 percent last year 
the report said the fourthquarter figure was revised downward 
from the 38 percent annual rate reported initially to 36 percent 
today 
some economists including chairman michael boskin of president 
bushs council of economic advisers had attributed the 
sluggishness in the fourth quarter in part to the effects of the 
fourth coldest december on record hurricane hugo and the san 
francisco bayarea earthquake 
most of the upward revision was attributed to a 
betterthananticipated trade performance the december trade 
deficit was not available when the advance gnp estimate was made 
the new report said exports climbed at an annual rate of 86 
percent in the fourth quarter compared with the advance estimate 
of 49 percent imports grew by 2 percent in the revised report 
instead of 75 percent first reported 
business inventories meanwhile were lowered from an initial 
489 percent increase to a 196 percent gain today 
other changes included personal consumption up 04 percent 
rather than the 01 percent decline first reported 
but business investment declined 64 percent in the latest 
estimate compared with a 3 percent decline in the first 
despite the improvement in fourthquarter growth several jolts 
from recent economic indicators have prompted some analysts to 
question whether the nations manufacturing economy will be able to 
avoid further deterioration this year and whether it will spread to 
other areas 
there is just not any evidence that the manufacturing sector 
has any strength said paul getman an economist with regional 
financial associates in west chester pa the question is whether 
this weakness in manufacturing will spread to other sectors of the 
economy 
the latest jolt to the current quarters growth was the commerce 
departments report on tuesday that orders to us factories for 
durable goods plummeted 105 percent last month in their steepest 
fall in 32 years of government recordkeeping 
the report signifies an ongoing recession for a chunk of the 
us manufacturing sector said allen sinai chief economist for 
the boston co 
the sharp decline is another sign well see virtually no real 
economic growth in the first quarter added jerry jasinowski 
president of the national association of manufacturers youve 
got pockets of recession in sectors such as automobiles surrounded 
by an absence of activity in the economy in general 
less than two weeks ago the commerce department reported that 
industrial production in january fell 12 percent its largest drop 
since falling 13 percent four years earlier 
the economic weakness has prompted the bush administration and 
many economists to urge the federal reserve to permit interest 
rates to fall further and thus stimulate the economy the central 
bank has kept a tight rein on credit for a year in an attempt to 
drive down inflation 
but the government reported last week that consumer prices rose 
a hefty 11 percent last month the largest advance since a 14 
percent gain 10 years ago and fed chairman alan greenspan 
indicated in congressional testimony that the central bank is 
unlikely to loosen its grip soon 
the feds tightmoney policy is blamed for economic growth 
slowing from 3 percent during the third quarter of 1989 
however two recent surveys indicate optimism that while 
economic activity will continue to be sluggish this year the 
economy will avoid sliding into a recession 
eightytwo percent of the executives questioned in a national 
association of manufacturers poll said 1990 will produce slow 
growth but no recession 
and 606 percent of the professional forecasters surveyed by the 
national association of business economists said they believe the 
economy will avoid a recession for the next three years 
but the latter survey found the economy is in a danger 
zone and the probability of a recession is not trivial 
