<TEXT>
the soviet legislature today overwhelmingly 
approved a bill that would allow citizens to lease land and 
bequeath it to their children for the first time since peasants 
were stripped of their farms under stalin 
the legislature first voted on each chapter of the 52article 
law separately and then approved the entire law 3497 with 12 
abstentions 
it is part of a package of measures designed to give force of 
law to the economic and social reforms championed by president 
mikhail s gorbachev the official tass news agency called it a 
major legal document of soviet economic reform 
according to the current soviet constitution all land in the 
soviet union is the property of the state 
the government hopes that if this is changed to allow peasants 
on collective or stateowned farms to acquire their own plots 
productivity on that land will increase productivity on 
stateowned and collective farms currently is notoriously low 
the congress of peoples deputies the supreme soviets parent 
body will be asked to amend the constitution to incorporate the 
new law when it meets march 12 
todays fourhour session was the third time the supreme soviet 
considered the law on land during debate on the bill earlier this 
month about 150 proposals and criticisms were made 
alexander nikonov president of the soviet agricultural academy 
who submitted the bill said about 40 percent of the original draft 
had been revised 
the law states that land is the property of the people living on 
a given territory and that every soviet citizen has the right to a 
piece of land 
land would be distributed by collective farms or in the case of 
city dwellers or other who wanted to hold land by local officials 
the land would not actually be purchased but leased and 
selling it would be illegal according to the law plots would be 
subject to taxes but could be bequeathed to the holders children 
the state would set land prices 
supreme soviet deputy pavel bunich an economist said a 
nationwide evaluation of the land would have to be carried out 
before any distribution could begin 
he said he was concerned that local governments would make 
available only undesirable land 
the law represents a major step forward in wresting control of 
the land from the state the bolsheviks socialized land in 1918 
which took away holdings from many city dwellers peasants were 
allowed to keep land until the brutal policy of collectivization 
went into effect in the late 1920s 
millions of peasants died in labor camps or of famine as a 
result of stalins collectivization plan which crippled soviet 
agriculture 
in action tuesday the legislature approved by a wide margin the 
creation of a much stronger soviet presidency an office gorbachev 
is widely expected to hold 
subject to final approval by the congress of peoples deputies 
the president will be granted powers to veto laws unilaterally 
declare states of emergency and name the prime minister according 
to a copy of the bill shown to western reporters 
gorbachev who chaired the legislatures proceedings emphasized 
he has not yet been elected president and said he has even 
considered refusing the office but few expect the 58yearold 
communist party chief not to be chosen 
according to vice president anatoly i lukyanov the supreme 
soviet is to meet in closed session on thursday to discuss the 
ethnic conflict between the two soviet republics of armenia and 
azerbaijan now in its third year 
</TEXT>
