<TEXT>
atlantis rocketed into the nighttime 
sky after five postponements and carried a spy satellite into orbit 
today riding a dazzling 700foot column of fire seen for hundreds 
of miles 
after waiting out clouds and rain the shuttle lifted off at 
251 am sending brilliant light and a shock wave across the 
darkened seaside space center 
the craft carrying a fiveman allmilitary crew on a secret 
mission expected to last four days disappeared into clouds in just 
38 seconds leaving briefly a glow like a shrouded full moon 
two hours later nasa shut down public commentary about the 
classified mission and spokesman bruce buckingham said at midday 
today that silence meant all was well 
the fact that we havent heard anything indicates that all is 
going to according to plan said buckingham if something out 
of the ordinary takes place well be informed 
observers as far north as washington dc reported seeing the 
light of atlantis rockets as the craft followed a route never 
before taken by a shuttle 
nasa administrator dick truly congratulated the launch team 
noting it was a tough one to get off but a great job 
no comment was heard from atlantis astronauts and launch 
director bob sieck said at a news conference the crew was pretty 
quiet and very patient 
weather threatened a sixth delay of the mission and the launch 
first targeted for last thursday was in doubt until the final 
moments 
nasa halted the countdown for about two hours to wait for clouds 
and light rain to move through the countdown was restarted at nine 
minutes paused briefly for a final weather check then ticked 
smoothly on to lift off 
as the rocket ignited light burst from the launch pad and 
leaped from cloud to cloud as far as the eye could see water 
surrounding the pad was gilded with light from the brilliant 
cascade of fire powering atlantis 
the first two scheduled launches were halted by a combination of 
an astronauts illness and uncertain weather the third and fifth 
tries were blocked by bad weather and the fourth by a failed 
computer 
