<TEXT>
labels on meat and poultry products will have 
to be more specific when certain flavorings are used the 
agriculture department said wednesday 
federal rules are being changed effective march 1 to require 
proteinaceous material derived from livestock poultry eggs 
milk plants and yeast to be listed on labels by their names 
in the past such substances could be listed simply as 
flavorings or similar terms 
for example a popular flavor agent or enhancer used for 
years in hot dogs will have to be labeled milk protein 
hydrolyzate 
lester m crawford administrator of the departments food 
safety and inspection service said the new rule which was 
proposed in august 1987 was adopted to better protect the 
public health and serve the consumers right to know whats in 
food products 
for many years the agency has required labels for meat and 
poultry products to list all ingredients he said however an 
exception was made to allow natural flavoring and similar terms 
to designate substances which are often added as flavor enhancers 
emulsifiers stabilizers binders extenders and nutrient sources 
in products such as frankfurthers and bologna 
crawford said the exception was allowed because the additives 
were primarily flavorings in meat and poultry products and did not 
make a significant nutritional contribution 
but he said the agencys paramount concern is public health 
and that it was found some people can have severe allergic 
reactions to these substances 
the agency is also concerned about a marked increase in the 
use of these ingredients during the last decade crawford said 
some manufacturers may be using the substances inappropriately as 
lowcost meat replacements 
now he said consumers with allergies to certain substances can 
tell if the product contains those ingredients 
crawford said meat and poultry processors will be allowed to 
make label changes over six months although the agency is working 
closely with the companies to speed it up 
at least one company is adding a stick on label to its 
regular packaging to further define the product ingredients he 
said 
</TEXT>
