three days of informal cambodian peace 
talks ended thursday with delegates still deadlocked on how to run 
the country until a new government can be elected the cohost of 
the negotiations said 
no major breakthroughs had been expected talks at a higher 
level are planned this month in paris 
the jakarta meeting focused on an australian proposal to have 
the united nations run cambodia until elections and to deploy an 
international peacekeeping force to ensure security 
the five permanent un security council members britain 
china france the soviet union and the united states support 
the australian plan it was proposed after formal peace talks in 
paris broke down last summer largely over the question of how the 
cambodian factions would share power before elections 
the vietnamesebacked government of cambodia and the 
threeparty guerrilla coalition fighting it appear to agree on 
un supervision of elections but they differ on who should be in 
charge of cambodia until the vote 
premier hun sen contends that dismantling the present 
administration could enable the communist khmer rouge guerrillas to 
seize power 
khmer rouge spokesmen have expressed reservations over the 
australian plan but have not announced a full policy decision 
prince norodom sihanouk and son sann leaders of the two 
noncommunist guerrilla groups have welcomed the australian 
proposal 
prime minister ali atlatas of indonesia said the talks ended 
early thursday with delegates unable to reach agreement he said no 
document was issued 
in addition to the four cambodian factions the talks included 
delegates from france laos the united nations and the association 
of southeast asian nations brunei indonesia malaysia the 
philippines singapore and thailand 
millions have been killed in cambodia since 1970 when a coup 
ended three decades of rule by sihanouk the khmer rouge took power 
in 1975 after a civil war and then killed hundreds of thousands of 
people in trying to create a new agrarian society 
vietnam invaded in late 1978 to oust the khmer rouge but never 
was able to completely stamp out the guerrilla resistance which 
holds cambodias seat in the un general assembly vietnam said it 
withdrew the last of its troops from cambodia last fall but there 
have been allegations that some soldiers and advisers have returned 
to help support government troops 
under the australian plan the un seat would be declared 
vacant until a new government was formed after elections 
australias foreign minister gareth evans also proposed a 
supreme national council with delegates from each of the four 
factions to hold the countrys sovereignty during the transition 
