and riot police to suppress protests last week by rebellious 
students calling for multiparty democracy 
tear gas stun grenades and truncheons were let loose in abidjan 
on demonstrators usually armed only with signs 
but houphouetboigny who has governed since the countrys 1960 
independence from france responded positively to more moderate 
demands for cuts in cabinet ministers salaries and the cost of 
board and lodging at the state university 
the ivorian leader has rejected previous demands for a 
multiparty state arguing that the system endangers national unity 
on a continent wracked by tribal rivalries 
france apparently intent on safeguarding its interests in 
former colonies apparently agrees paris recently advised guinea 
to model political reforms on the ivory coast not a multiparty 
democracy 
there are some multiparty states that have no democracy and 
some oneparty states that practice democracy like ivory 
coast former french prime minister jacques chirac commented in 
abidjan this week 
omar bongo of gabon another beleaguered west african leader 
identified the immediate cause of strikes and protests in the 
region he blamed falling purchasing power provoked by the 
austerity programs of the international monetary fund in an 
interview with radio france international this week 
bongos 22yearold civilian rule is threatened by strikes and 
protests that have closed librevilles airport electricity cuts 
that caused the deaths of five patients in the capitals hospital 
wednesday and rampaging students who forced schools to close 
this weeks strikes are over dissatisfaction with political 
reforms announced friday including the replacement of the 
discredited democratic party with a social democratic rally which 
bongo said is open to all political ideas 
the change falls short of promises bongo made after an octoe 
coup attempt to consider transforming gabon into a multiparty 
democracy 
the upheaval in gabon follows 10 years of recession caused by 
slumping prices of the commodities that underpin african economies 
it has brought unemployment salary cuts and inflation 
austerity measures forced by the international monetary fund and 
world bank in return for loans have caused hardships that 
protesters say have become unbearable 
ivorian authorities this week proposed cuts of between 15 
percent and 40 percent in the salaries of government employees who 
have suffered an eightyear wage freeze in addition to a new 10 
percent income tax 
for a messenger earning the minimum wage of 125 that means 
earning 25 percent less in a country where a bag of rice to feed a 
family for a month costs 30 and rent for two rooms more than 40 
ivory coast is one of the luckier countries the minimum monthly 
salary in ghana nigeria or sierra leone is not enough to buy a bag 
of rice 
the international monetary fund and world bank are easy targets 
for attack gambian reporter baboucar m gaye coined a new term 
our country has been imfd he declared in a report 
he said economic problems are compounded by the convertible 
central african franc of 11 west african states that is 
underwritten by the french treasury and is set at an inflated rate 
that encourages huge import and customs duties and discourages 
foreign investors 
bata shoe company which operates in the most ecnomically 
difficult african nations including marxist ethiopia closed its 
factory in ivory coast because smugglers could import shoes more 
cheaply than the company could import its raw materials 
the world bank official also pointed to the corruption and 
lavish official lifestyles that have drained state coffers and 
angered impoverished west africans into revolt 
gambians criticized extravagant celebrations in february marking 
25 years of independence from britain that were attended by 
britains princess anne and george bush jr the us presidents 
son 
most gambians are muttering privately that the state of 
austerity should have compelled us to forgo any celebrations 
gaye said 
some leaders blame unidentified outside sources for their 
troubles 
nigers gen ali saibou wednesday accused a small group of 
malcontents plotting to destabilize and throw niger into 
chaos of engineering violent student protests in which troops 
have killed at least three demonstrators 
saibou promised democracy when he led a 1987 coup but recently 
declared the military would not surrender power and announced plans 
for a constitution allowing only one political party 
