a courtbacked agreement on safety measures 
for allterrain vehicles has failed to result in the expected sharp 
decline in injuries and deaths the chairman of a house panel said 
wednesday 
rep doug barnard dga whose subcommittee helped prompt a 
1988 agreement banning new sales of threewheeled offtheroad 
vehicles questioned the agressiveness of the federal consumer 
product safety commission in enforcing safety provisions for atvs 
your advocacy to me comes short barnard told commission 
chairman jacqueline jonessmith 
in a hearing before barnards house government operations 
subcommittee safety experts said that offroad vehicles remain 
inherently unstable and deceptively dangerous for their riders 
they said that there are some 25 million of the existing 
threewheeled models and the newer fourwheel versions many of 
them ridden primarily by children they said an agreement by 
manufacturers not to sell adultsized vehicles for use by children 
under 16 is being ignored 
atvs are kidkillers plain and simple said charles chvala 
