restrict the vehicles 
the industry defended its action and safety record 
riding an atv is far less risky than a number of other popular 
activities said howard p willens lobbyist for distributers of 
honda kawasaki suzuki and yamaha brand vehicles 
distributors of the three and fourwheeled vehicles agreed to a 
consent decree with the federal government in 1988 on safety steps 
for atvs the order signed by federal judge gerhard gesell was in 
response to a suit by the consumer product safety commission after 
congressional hearings 
as part of the agreement the industry agreed to sell only 
fourwheeled versions in the future but there was no recall of 
existing threewheel models it also required safety warnings and 
public awareness campaigns and sale of adultsize vehicles only 
for use by people 16 or over 
jonessmith defended that agreement and the commissions 
enforcement she said deaths and injuries due to the vehicles have 
declined from 350 in 1986 to approximately 300 annually about 40 
percent of the deaths are children under 16 she said 
she said an undercover investigation by the cpsc staff found a 
majority of dealers recommended vehicles not appropriate for a 
purchaser seeking a vehicle for a 13yearold child she said 
distributers should take steps to make their dealers comply with 
age requirements 
janine jagger assistant professor of neurosurgery at the 
university of virginia said the consent decree is a safety 
sham that has not lessened risk or changed the practices of 
this irresponsible and arrogant industry 
willens the industry lobbyist said the injury rate has dropped 
52 percent since 1985 and the fatality rate 27 percent 
willens said most fatalities were due to extreme forms of 
vehicle misuse 
