<TEXT>
growing numbers of americans are getting their 
medical care at walkin clinics and other freestanding centers 
that are inadequately regulated to ensure quality care a 
congressional report said wednesday 
the general accounting office said states dont license or 
regulate most types of freestanding medical facilities and they 
impose few penalties when problems are uncovered at licensed 
centers 
the report was released by rep edward roybal dcalif who 
said the lack of oversight permits abuses in patient care to 
occur with increasing frequency 
when americans walk into unlicensed facilities they walk in 
with blindfolds unaware of the competence of the provider or of 
the quality of care they will receive said roybal who chairs 
the house select committee on aging and its subcommittee on health 
and longterm care 
the gao report had been requested by roybals predecessor as 
subcommittee chairman the late rep claude pepper dfla 
it covers freestanding facilities such as walkin health 
clinics 24hour emergency centers mental health centers cancer 
treatment facilities cardiac catheterization laboratories 
surgical centers and alcohol and drug abuse treatment facilities 
states have been slow to license freestanding providers 
further they have limited plans to expand licensing 
requirements the gao said no one else currently fills the 
gaps consumers therefore do not have adequate assurance that 
unlicensed freestanding providers are giving quality care 
freestanding medical clinics and health maintenance 
organizations have expanded rapidly in recent years as a result of 
efforts to control health care costs developing technology and 
increased competition the gao said 
roybal noted that before costcontrol rules were imposed on 
hospitals in the early 1980s 95 percent of cataract surgeries were 
performed in hospitals he said 95 percent of the operations now 
are performed outside of hopsitals to avoid those cost controls 
a study prepared for the national conference of state 
legislatures estimated that up to 40 percent of diagnostic 
procedures and surgeries are being done outside hospitals 
among the findings in the gao report 
only montana and new york require licenses for all the types of 
healthcare centers operating in their states 
no state licenses or otherwise regulates cancer treatment 
centers or pain control centers although such centers are 
operating in 1418 states 
only virginia and california license cardiac catheterization 
laboratories although the procedure sometimes can involve 
complications that result in death stroke heart attack or 
uncontrolled hemorrhaging 
less than half the states require licenses for independent 
clinical laboratories walkin clinics or outpatient psychiatric 
centers 
states frequently did not know what types and numbers of 
freestanding clinics were operating within their borders 
the gao found that even those centers that are licensed by the 
states are subject to few sanctions in fiscal 1987 for example 
23000 freestanding health facilities were licensed by the states 
of which 165 were cited for deficiences and 28 had their licenses 
suspended or revoked 
officials in 36 states expressed concerns about the adequacy of 
their oversight of freestanding centers but most had no plans to 
regulate more facilities the gao said 
