prices farmers got for raw products declined 
06 percent from january to february but overall commodity index 
still averaged 27 percent more than a year ago the agriculture 
department said wednesday 
lower prices for milk eggs lettuce and wheat were mostly 
responsible for the decline from january the departments 
agricultural statistics board said in its preliminary report 
however the report said higher prices for cattle broiler and 
tomatoes partly offset the decline for the other commodities during 
the month 
tomato prices for february were at the highest level of 
records the report said during the past two months prices 
have been about twice the previous record established in march of 
1985 
the price climb was due to short supplies caused by the december 
freeze in florida in december the report said 
on the other hand the report said the drop in milk prices paid 
to farmers which had been at record levels was largest 
monthtomonth decline ever recorded and the egg price drop was 
said to be the thirdlargest on record 
the report did not include new figures on farm expenses those 
are computed every three months in january however new quarterly 
figures showed that prices paid by farmers were up 11 percent from 
october the previous reading and averaged 29 percent more than a 
year earlier 
department economists say the net cash income of farmers in 1990 
may be in the range of 52 billion to 57 billion compared with 
about 53 billion in 1989 
net cash income is the money nationally that farmers have left 
from gross cash income during a calendar year after deducting cash 
expenses it includes government payments and proceeds from crops 
grown previously but sold during the year 
in another method taking into account changes in inventories 
depreciation and other allowances during a calendar year shows that 
1990 net farm income may be in a range of 44 billion to 49 
billion compared with 48 billion last year 
consumer food prices are forecast by usda economists to rise 3 
percent to 5 percent this year after posting an average gain of 57 
percent in 1989 the sharpest rise since 1981 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter told congress on wednesday 
that farm commodity prices are expected to be relatively 
favorable in 1990 because of strong demand and declining 
inventories of most crops he said feed grains and soybeans may be 
exceptions however 
production may rise as acreage reduction requirements for 
wheat cotton and rice are lessened bringing more acreage into 
production he told a senate appropriation subcommittee 
based on the preliminary figures the february price index for 
livestock and poultry was down 06 percent from january but was up 
82 percent from february 1989 
milk prices dropped 80 cents from january to 1490 per 100 
pounds but were still 180 more than a year ago 
crop prices overall dropped 07 percent from december and were 
29 percent below the yearearlier average 
the report said 
