urging the use of the moneys to cut taxes was defeated by majority 
democrats 
the fight was over a competing pair of nonbinding resolutions 
and was therefore largely symbolic nonetheless it provided a 
preview of a partisan dispute likely to reverberate through 
congress for years what to do with billions of dollars in planned 
military spending that have been made unnecessary by easing 
eastwest tensions 
the senate voted 7919 for language by liberal democrats led by 
sens edward kennedy dmass and james sasser dtenn urging 
the senate to use defense savings mainly to help balance the 
federal budget as lesser priorities they said the savings should 
also be used to address urgent national priorities such as 
antidrug and education efforts and to cut taxes for working men 
and women 
minutes later senators voted 5048 against a rival proposal 
from 12 gop conservatives led by sen phil gramm of texas 
recommending that money siphoned from the pentagons budget be 
returned to americas taxpayers the republicans said that would 
include tax deductions for child care a capital gains tax rate 
cut a lowering of other tax rates and additional ideas 
democrats argued that the large tax cuts of 1981 did not improve 
the nations economy and that the country has too many unaddressed 
problems 
its high time we quit squandering the treasury of this nation 
for overly sophisticated weapons systems sasser said we need 
to take this peace dividend and we need to apply these funds 
wisely 
republicans countered that in the years following the vietnam 
war moneys taken from the pentagon budget were spent fruitlessly 
by congress a scenario that should be avoided 
the term peace dividend while widely used can be 
misleading technically with the government running large deficits 
each year reductions in the pentagons budget will not leave the 
government with surplus dollars to spend the congressional budget 
office expects the deficit in fiscal 1991 which begins oct 1 
to be 138 billion 
nonetheless since the warsaw pact began deteriorating late last 
year lawmakers have been arguing over what to do with the money 
that everyone had assumed would be used for defense spending 
in his budget for the fiscal year that will begin oct 1 
president bush proposed pentagon spending of 2921 billion that 
is 53 billion more than is being spent this year but 39 billion 
below the amount that would have been needed to keep pace with 
inflation 
most democrats and some republicans have said bushs request is 
too high and most lawmakers expect congress to approve a figure 
that is several billion dollars lower 
the resolutions were offered as amendments to a bill that would 
allow the government to spend 125 million to set up programs for 
volunteers 
in the 7919 vote by which the senate adopted the democratic 
peace dividend resolution those voting no were 
christopher s bond rmo john chafee rri john danforth 
rmo bob dole rkan pete v domenici rnm jake garn 
rutah charles grassley riowa jesse helms rnc gordon 
