<TEXT>
a study showing that a vietnamera program 
failed to help lowaptitude soldiers in later civilian life was 
disputed in congressional testimony wednesday opening a debate on 
whether the military can promote social improvement 
the house veterans affairs subcommittee hearing concerned 
project 100000 under which defense secretary robert s 
mcnamara tried to fight the vietnam war and the war on poverty in 
one action 
rep lane evans dill chairman of the subcommittee on 
oversight and investigations said he wanted to determine whether 
project 100000 was a legitimate great society social program 
or was project 100000 a calculated even cynical means to 
satisfy the manpower needs of the armed forces and at the same time 
lessen domestic opposition to the war in vietnam he asked 
under the program the pentagon lowered the physical and mental 
standards for entry into the armed services in exchange the new 
members of the service were promised remedial education and 
training 
about 300000 enlisted under that program from 1966 to 1971 
twothirds in the army fiftyfour percent were volunteers 
half came from the south more than 40 percent were members of 
minority groups the average reading ability was at the sixth grade 
level 
most went to combat or to soft skill jobs such as food 
service supply wire communications motor transport and 
automotive repair 
flaws in the enlistment test allowed another group of about 
300000 also lacking the traditional qualifications to enter the 
military from 1976 to 1980 
according to the study the project 100000 veterans wound up 
earning 5000 to 7000 less per year than their nonveteran 
counterparts veterans were more likely to be unemployed less 
likely to be married and more likely to have been divorced 
the lowaptitude veterans who served from 1976 to 1980 were not 
found to be better off economically educationally or socially than 
their nonveteran counterparts there were no significant 
differences in unemployment kinds of jobs held or average income 
the report said 
but the veterans had less formal education higher divorce rates 
and were more likely to be unhappy with their jobs 
project 100000s social promises were not kept social 
scientist janice h laurence testified 
laurence is a senior scientist with human resources research 
organization the alexandria vabased group that conducted the 
study for the defense department 
she suggested that two years in the military was not enough time 
to counter characteristics acquired over 18 years of growing up 
she noted that 4 percent of the project 100000 continued with 
military careers while evans noted that many were denied 
reenlistment because of subsequent low test scores 
to compensate for the deficits which the underprivileged bring 
with them would require more than a little extra training and 
maybe even a complete restructuring of current pedagogical 
practices or content she said 
the results were disputed by researcher william e beusse who 
studied project 100000 army veterans in the early 1970s and 
reached opposite conclusions 
beusse said he used a far stricter sampling methods producing 
more accurate results he acknowledged that veterans would have 
lost seniority and the opportunity to enter a tight job market 
in an age of dramatically reduced threat the cost of even a 
scaleddown peacetime force may be too expensive for defense to 
be its only product beusse argued society may come to demand 
that the military assist in addressing other national needs such as 
providing largescale manpower training for low aptitude men and 
women in this area the military has more than proven its 
capability to perform 
wayne s sellman head of recruiting policy for the pentagon 
said he believed the longterm decline in performance by 
lowaptitude veterans may have been due to the gradual distancing 
from the discipline and highly organized life that the military 
provided point also made by laurence 
he said sellmans study caught veterans fresh from the service 
while laurence caught them later 
</TEXT>
