as many as 37 million young americans could 
be eligible for the new belowminimum training wage that takes 
effect april 1 along with the first increase in the minimum wage 
since 1981 the labor department said wednesday 
but few employers will develop training programs that will 
permit them to pay the lower wage beyond the 90day limit the 
department predicted 
only firms that develop onthejob training programs may pay 
workers 16 to 19 the lower wage for a second 90day period 
starting april 1 employers can pay teenagers new to the job 
market 335 an hour thats the same amount as the current minimum 
wage which will increase to 380 an hour on april 1 1991 the 
regular minimum wage will go to 425 an hour while the training 
wage will rise to 361 
guidelines announced by the department wednesday require 
employers who want to pay the lower wage for the second 90day 
period to develop training programs that provide knowledge and 
skills beyond those customarily learned by observation and 
incidental work exposure 
the programs must include training for both jobspecific 
skills such as cleaning equipment or running a cash register 
and personal skills such as courtesy and punctuality the 
guidelines said 
when congress debated the measure last year democrats opposed a 
training wage but were forced to concede the point to president 
bush to avoid a veto democrats also had to scale back their final 
minimumwage target since bush had vetoed a measure earlier that 
called for an increase to 455 an hour 
in return bush agreed to have the minimum wage reach 425 nine 
months earlier than he had proposed and also accepted a far more 
restricted training wage than he sought earlier 
originally bush had wanted to allow the lower wage to be paid 
to all workers regardless of age for their first six months on 
any new job regardless of past work experience 
