<TEXT>
federal financing for aids prevention is unlikely 
to continue to grow as fast in the 1990s as it did during the 
epidemics first decade the centers for disease control warns in a 
draft of a new report 
program needs can be expected to continue to grow at a pace 
that will probably exceed available resources the atlantabased 
agency said in the draft of its strategic plan for prevention of 
hiv infection 1990 and beyond 
we must approach our planning with an awareness of these 
changes and a willingness to change it said 
the agencys congressional appropriation for aids programs in 
the current fiscal year is 443 million up 17 percent from 19889 
president bushs request for the next fiscal year is 509 million 
an increase of less than 15 percent 
the rapid increase in funding in the mid80s is leveling 
off said dr gary noble deputy director for aids programs 
theres a growing recognition that aids has to compete with all 
the other health problems and all the other national priorities 
the funding cant continue to increase at the rate that it 
did without curtailing other high priority programs 
the 50page report which is being circulated to public health 
professionals aids experts and educators outlines the agencys 
goals and objectives for aids based on 16 planning assumptions 
among those assumptions 
the aids epidemic is actually composed of multiple 
subepidemics chiefly among homosexual men selected racial 
and ethnic minority populations and intravenous drug abusers 
our efforts to intervene must be tailored to the specific 
needs of those subpopulations noble said 
the rate of change in the epidemic is not the same for each of 
those subepidemics he added noting a slowing of aids in some 
gay white male bigcity populations while aids continues to soar 
among intravenous drug abusers 
human immunodeficiency virus the aids virus causes a 
lifelong persistent infection usually leading to progressive 
illness and death although 10 years or more can pass between 
initial infection and illness 
behaviors are major determinants of hiv infection 
including gay male sex multiple sex partners and having sex or 
sharing drug needles with infected people 
the report says that to prevent sexaul transmission of aids the 
cdc needs to support and promote counseling testing referral and 
notification of sexual partners 
opportunities for medical interventions to prolong the life of 
aidsinfected people will be lost unless major barriers to testing 
programs such as fear of public exposure and discrimination are 
removed it says 
but some aids activists have said testing and counseling arent 
nearly enough 
once we test all these people what are we going to do with 
them mike merdian executive director of the national 
association of people with aids said in comments published in 
wednesdays atlanta constitution you cant talk about testing 
without talking about treatment 
merdian did not return calls for further comment wednesday 
the draft report said the cdc should develop and evaluate better 
tests for aidsrelated viruses to better prevent transmission 
through the blood supply the agency noted that the risk of aids 
transmission through blood transfusion is small but still exists 
with current testing procedures 
recommendations in the plan are not specific suggestions to each 
and every state and local health agency but rather are a plan 
communicating generally to the public noble said 
after public comment and possible revisions the cdc report is 
scheduled for release in june 
the cdc estimates that 1 million americans are infected with 
hiv while another 5200057000 aids cases will be diagnosed this 
year more than 117000 aids cases have been reported since 1981 
</TEXT>
