<TEXT>
senate leaders and the bush administration 
reached an accord wednesday on pollution controls for automobiles 
removing a major obstacle to agreement on a compromise clean air 
bill senate sources said 
closeddoor negotiations continued into the evening over details 
about new acid rain controls but sources close to the talks said 
those issues were unlikely to scuttle the rest of the pollution 
control package which has been worked out in three weeks of 
bargaining 
disagreements over acid rain might be set aside and be thrashed 
out on the senate floor if the differences involving largely 
disagreements among senators are not resolved said an aide to one 
senator who has been close to the private talks 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said he planned 
to bring the clean air bill to the senate floor on thursday and had 
no desire to extend the private bargaining with the administration 
for another day 
the talks which had gone past midnight twice this week 
continued into the evening as negotiators focused on remaining 
disagreements over provisions on controlling acid rain it was the 
only remaining area of disagreement the sources said 
while senate leaders and the bush administration have agreed on 
most of the acid rain provision individual senators have not 
a group of midwest senators have threatened to filibuster 
against the clean air bill if they do not receive help in paying 
for the expensive pollution controls that would be required at many 
of that regions coalfired electric plants have to meet the deep 
cuts required for acid rain pollution 
other senators have balked at such cotsharing because they 
argued their states already have paid to clean up their electric 
plants these same senators however have expressed concern that 
the new pollution controls might inhibit growth of electric 
capacity in their states 
the negotiations turned to the acid rain issue after the two 
sides agreed on how to curb emissions from automobiles and reduce 
the smog problem that has plagued many urban areas 
the issue had been among the most contentious under discussion 
the senate bill called for two rounds of tough emission controls on 
automobiles to reduce urban smog 
the bush administration however had strongly objected to the 
second round of controls saying they were too expensive and 
provided only marginal benefits senate authors of the legislation 
however argued the additional controls were needed for some of the 
most polluted urban centers to achieve clean air 
according to sources who spoke on condition of anonymity the 
compromise agreement calls for the socalled tier 2 controls to go 
into effect nationwide only if 11 of 27 cities now considered to 
have serious air pollution problems fail to make adequate 
progress in meeting federal air quality standards by late in this 
decade 
environmentalists criticized the compromise as being almost as 
bad as not have a second round of emission controls at all they 
argued that it is unlikely that 11 the 27 cities would not be able 
to achieve the federal standards since the group of 27 does not 
include the eight of the countrys most polluted cities which are 
in categories of severe or extreme pollution 
you could have cities with a total of 80 million people not in 
federal air quality attainment and still not have a tier 2 
said gene karpinski executive director of the us public interest 
research group an environmental group 
the senateadminstration talks earlier this week produced 
tentative agreements on how to control toxic chemicals from 
industrial plants and on curbing smogcausing pollutants from an 
array of stationery sources from chemical plants to dry cleaners 
while most of the focus has been on the senate bill in recent 
weeks a different version remains in a house committee house 
speaker thomas s foley dwash said wednesday he hoped that bill 
could come up for floor consideration by april several months 
earlier than he previously had indicated 
