<TEXT>
more than 6600 hospital patients died and 
thousands more were injured through medical negligence in new york 
state in 1984 but few malpractice suits were filed said a harvard 
university study released wednesday 
although the survey involved only new york state researchers 
said they expect a nationwide survey would find similar results 
dr david axelrod the state health commissioner said the 
results pointed to major inequities in the medical malpractice 
system involving both compensating victims and deterring 
professional misconduct 
axelrod who backs a proposal for nofault malpractice 
insurance said he believed such a reform would improve the system 
because doctors would be less fearful that reporting negligence by 
colleagues would bring lawsuits upon themselves or their hospital 
but consumer rights groups and advocates for victims of medical 
negligence who oppose the nofault plan called for more 
government policing of doctors and stiffer penalties for those 
found guilty of negligence 
despite the thousands of instances of malpractice documented in 
the study only 26 doctors were disciplined in the state in 1984 
for negligence 
how can this be no ones fault asked elaine orourke 
pointing to her son who went into a brooklyn hospital for a 
bedwetting problem and came out brain damaged and confined to a 
wheelchair 
orourke and other members of her group stop hospital and 
medical errors frequently interrupted a news conference on the 
study with demands that criminal penalties be adopted for 
healthcare workers found guilty of negligent acts 
overall the study estimated that 37 percent of those 
hospitalized sustained an injury in the hospital that resulted in 
measurable disability 
the researchers said that would translate into 99000 injuries 
out of 27 million people hospitalized statewide in 1984 
most of the injuries were relatively minor 70 percent of 
patients recovered completely within six months but 14 percent 
were fatal a rate which translated into more than 13000 deaths in 
1984 
fiftyone percent of the fatal injuries resulted from 
negligence the study found but it noted that many of the deaths 
occurred in patients who had greatly shortened life expectancies 
from their underlying diseases 
doctors and hospitals are required by state law to report all 
cases of possible medical misconduct however peter slocum a 
health department spokesman said the state received only 1525 
reports of possible misconduct in 1984 and only 161 came from 
physicians or hospitals 
axelrod denied that there was a code of silence among health 
care providers over reporting negligence cases he blamed the 
current tort system which he said deters compliance with the 
law 
a large number of adverse events that occur in institutions 
are not currently being reported to us he said 
the number of malpractice claims filed against doctors and 
hospitals was only about 10 percent of the total number of 
negligent injuries the study found of the patients who were found 
in the study to have been injured because of negligence only 2 
percent filed malpractice claims 
the medical society of the state of new york which supports 
axelrods calls for malpractice reform applauded the report and 
said the current tort system was a grotesque failure 
it overcompensates some but tragically it fails to compensate 
many many people who are the victims of inadequate medical care 
spokesman gerard l conway told the news conference 
the new york state trial lawyers association issued a statement 
saying the states malpractice crisis was not the fault of the 
legal system but rather is caused by negligent and substandard 
care by doctors 
the fouryear 31million study one of the most comprehensive 
ever undertaken involved a review of the records of more than 
30000 patients from 51 randomly selected hospitals in new york 
state 
the researchers stressed that the findings could not be applied 
to hospitals today since most hospitals have taken a variety of 
steps since 1984 to improve patient care 
the study looked at cases of unintended injury which was 
defined as one caused by medical management rather than by the 
disease process they included errors in performing medical 
procedures as well as diagnostic errors and improper or omitted 
care 
</TEXT>
