<TEXT>
eighteen ships were stuck wednesday 
in the gulf of st lawrence in what the canadian coast said were 
the worst ice conditions on the waterway in 10 years 
andy maillet assistant coast guard ice operations officer said 
the combination of an early winter extremely low temperatures and 
easterly winds had created a near impenetrable layer of ice 
some of these ships have been out there quite a long time 
maillet said some of them have been stuck for four or five 
days 
the ice driven by easterly winds runs in a line from the 
strait of belle isle to the gaspe peninsula and anticosti island 
it has been drifting generally in a southwest direction 
enabling it to press up against the newfoundland and cape breton 
coasts maillet said 
the ice has disrupted shipping for the past two weeks and left 
coast guard officials hoping for an early spring 
six icebreakers four from nova scotia and one each from 
newfoundland and quebec were trying to break the ships free and 
escort them to passable ice 
at one point last week 26 ships were stuck the numbers keep 
changing as some vessels break free 
once the ice pressure changes a little bit they are able to 
back away from the particular ice pan theyre in and then carry on 
their voyage said maillet but you lose one you gain another 
 
he said he expected poor shipping conditions would continue for 
a couple more weeks 
maillet said none of the 18 ships including tankers 
freighters and container vessels was in immediate danger 
although some were low on water and fuel 
none of them has run out of fuel yet we wont let them 
maillet said 
he warned the situation could change quickly however 
depending on where they get stuck they could fall into danger 
of drifting ashore he said 
eight of the icebound ships were trying to reach gulf ports 
while the other 10 were trying to get through the cabot strait to 
the open atlantic 
the coast guard had to take medication by helicopter to one ship 
last week while a search and rescue crew carried out a medical 
evacuation of a crewmember with a badly cut finger 
</TEXT>
