exxon corp was indicted on criminal charges in the nations worst 
oil spill 
i was tremendously relieved because i was worried that we were 
going to see some settlement that wasnt in the interests of 
alaska said state rep david finkelstein of anchorage 
the state lobbied the us justice department to reject the plea 
bargain with exxon saying it would hurt alaskas efforts to win 
civil damages from the multibilliondollar oil company 
we felt the proposed plea bargain did affect our civil 
litigation and we squawked about it gov steve cowper said 
cowper said it appeared from the fivecount indictment issued 
tuesday that the federal government was throwing the book at 
exxon and i think that is probably appropriate 
us attorney general dick thornburgh said tuesday that the plea 
bargain fell through because of state officials objections and 
because of exxons unwillingness to meet the governments terms 
several state officials alleged the plea negotiations were part 
of an attempt by the bush administration and exxon to limit the oil 
companys exposure to large criminal fines 
exxon has a very powerful influence theyre very powerful in 
the economic clout they carry in washington dc as well as in 
juneau it doesnt surprise me that they attempted to do an end 
run sen jay kerttula whose district includes part of 
oilfouled prince william sound said wednesday 
sen mike szymanski of anchorage said it appeared the 
administration was trying to cut a deal and let exxon at least 
evade the criminal prosecution which would then save them on the 
civil side 
while the federal government has handled the criminal case the 
state has focused on civil claims stemming from the spill the 
state also is prosecuting former tanker skipper joseph hazelwood on 
felony criminal mischief and other charges stemming from the spill 
the new york times in its thursday editions quoted 
unidentified justice department officials as saying the 
departments attempt to reach a plea bargain was motivated largely 
by the desire to avoid a long trial it might lose the officials 
said they face a difficult court battle to convict exxon and said 
the government remains open to the possibility of a negotiated 
settlement the newspaper reported 
the tanker exxon valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of 
north slope crude in the sound march 24 killing countless birds 
and marine mammals and disrupting alaskas lucrative fisheries 
under the proposed plea bargain the federal government would 
have abandoned its commitment to help the state in its civil 
litigation state attorney general douglas baily said 
state officials also criticized the justice department for the 
secrecy surrounding the plea negotiations rep gene kubina of 
valdez said the indictment ensures the criminal case will be heard 
in public 
finkelstein said it was in exxons best interest to reach a plea 
bargain privately before the indictment was filed now i think 
its much less likely that a settlement will occur in a form that 
would hurt alaska he said 
exxon faces more than 700 million in possible penalties if 
convicted the money would go into the federal treasury but 
federal law gives the judge discretion to order restoration of the 
environment 
state officials said any money from the case should go to 
restore the environment of the sound and the gulf of alaska to the 
condition it was in before the spill 
the money shouldnt just go into the federal treasury said 
sen fred zharoff of kodiak i think we ought to be looking at 
ways and means of protecting the resources 
szymanski maintained the federal government has an obligation to 
help restore the environment and improve the coast guards 
monitoring of tanker traffic out of valdez 
state officials said large penalties are needed to ensure exxon 
and other oil shippers take the precautions necessary to prevent 
oil spills 
when you get up there close to a billion dollars its bound 
to get their attention house speaker sam cotten said 
