<TEXT>
if you already have a halfdozen credit cards 
and hardly use them youre probably wondering why more banks are 
beseeching you to apply for theirs 
many use sales pitches that include waived annual fees 24hour 
card replacement protection instant 5000 cashadvance limits 
preapproved applications and bonuses that range from free 
travel to car rental discounts this aggressive marketing to peddle 
credit cards may seem even more curious in view of rising default 
rates for many types of loans a growing number of debttroubled 
banks a record number of bankruptcies and a slowly emerging 
backlash against the 1980s era of spending borrowed money 
credit cards nonetheless remain one of the most profitable 
segments of the banking industry the percentage of late payments 
remains relatively low and actually has declined compared with some 
years ago industry experts say 
moreover interest charges on many credit cards exceed 18 
percent much higher than most other types of consumer loans 
making them even more attractive to an industry struggling to find 
new ways of making money 
people who said the credit card market was saturated 3 or 4 or 
5 years ago probably had to swallow a good bit of that crow said 
bruce brittain head of britain associates inc an atlantabased 
marketing strategy consultant that researches credit card use 
even a few new credit cards discover from sears and and optima 
from american express have muscled into millions of wallets 
there also are indications that japan is headed this way with the 
jcb japan credit bureau card the most widely accepted plastic in 
the east 
there is no indication that credit card growth is leveling off 
daniel marx program associate at bankcard holders of america a 
washingtonbased consumer group said outstanding debt on all types 
of credit cards in 1989 totaled 182 billion vs 82 billion at 
the beginning of the decade 
last year 224 million americans held the two most common types 
of bank credit cards mastercard and visa vs 120 million in 1980 
he said 
banking experts say a catalyst for this explosion is the ease 
with which banks can obtain screening information about potential 
customers drastically lowering their cost of signing up 
creditworthy users 
banks once went on what amounted to fishing expeditions mailing 
applications en masse when the credit card business was in its 
infancy some banks simply sent the cards and hoped users would pay 
their bills now many banks first go to credit bureaus which 
routinely sell them computerized lists of names screened by age 
group income and debts 
banks can say i need the names of all males over 48 years 
old who make more than 75000 a year and have 15000 of available 
credit marx said 
the computer will spit out this information for a price 
theres a lot of this that goes on this is where you get your 
preapproved credit card you fit into a niche that the banks have 
drawn up 
this explains for example why a new yorker who has several 
cards may get a solicitation from a small bank in st louis to sign 
up for its visa or mastercharge or a californian will get one from 
an obscure bank in delaware 
what also has happened many experts say is that consumers have 
acquired so many cards they are becoming more selective about which 
ones they use this has intensified the competition 
a bank cant sit back anymore and wait for a customer to use 
its card said virginia stafford a spokeswoman for the american 
bankers association a washington trade group of commercial banks 
what the issuer has to do is make sure when you open your wallet 
you pull out its card not someone elses 
many credit card experts caution that users who are wondering 
whether to sign up for new cards should carefully read the fine 
print of their applications especially regarding interest rates 
and grace periods which can vary widely they also say the 
preapproved enticement in many cases simply means your name 
was culled from a preapproved list 
theyre still going to check your credit brittain said 
if they discover anything about you youre still going to get 
bounced 
others say the net effect of the marketing assault on credit 
card users is good mostly because it reflects competition that is 
providing more choices 
we feel that frankly its an opportunity for the consumer to 
shop said jay muzychenko vice president of the national 
foundation for consumer credit a creditcounseling organization in 
silver spring md 
our position is that bottom line you dont have to take the 
cards just because theyre offered 
