<TEXT>
a look at the souths political corridors 
before and after passage of the 1965 voting rights act reveals 
dramatic gains by blacks but it was only a first step toward black 
electoral victories 
in alabama it took a massive but mostly unheralded court case 
launched in mobile in the late 1970s to restructure scores of 
local governments that had used atlarge election systems to 
effectively bar blacks from office 
the voting rights act eliminated the voter registration 
roadblocks candidate qualification rules and other discriminatory 
practices that kept elected offices tantalizingly out of reach for 
blacks 
but it wasnt until the us senate extended the act in 1982 
that language was included protecting minorities from election laws 
with discriminatory effects even if their initial intent was not 
without having to prove intentional discrimination civil rights 
lawyers were able to attack the atlarge election systems that 
diluted black voting strength in cities and counties where blacks 
were the minority of the population 
the litigation was based largely on the mobile case styled 
bolden vs city of mobile which led to a ruling mandating the 
dismantling of the citys commission form of government the 
members of which were elected atlarge it was replaced with a 
sevenmember council elected by districts including at least three 
blackmajority districts 
by 1988 the use of atlarge elections had all but disappeared 
in alabama with court action the most crucial mechanism for 
change said historian peyton mccrary who studied the voting 
right acts impact on alabama and other southern states 
another historian chandler davidson of rice university has 
called it a second reconstruction 
as late as 1979 alabamas 400 municipalities had only 94 black 
city council members according to the alabama democratic 
conference the partys black political caucus 
but with the advent of the changeofgovernment litigation the 
number had climbed by 1989 to 410 black council members nearly 
onefifth of all council seats the group said the state is 
slightly more than onefourth black 
only a handful of alabamas 67 counties still use atlarge 
elections to pick commission members most in locales with small 
percentages of blacks 
once blacks and whites get on these governing boards and have 
to work together over time they begin to become friends said 
jerome gray field director for the black caucus 
but voters still split along racial lines when they go to the 
polls said historian robert j norrell of the university of 
alabama 
people can still win elections by appealing only to one 
race said norrell author of a book on the civil rights movement 
in tuskegee 
david ruffin editor of focus magazine the monthly public 
policy magazine of the joint center for political studies in 
washington dc puts the voting rights act in the context of the 
200yearold civil rights struggle 
its the 200year process of extending the franchise to every 
american he said this is one more step 
ruffin said sundays planned reenactment of the 
selmatomontgomery march is part of the continuing process of 
political change 
the whole reason we were out in the streets in the 60s was to 
be part of the establishment he said martin luther king 
wanted to join this great american enterprise he wanted to be a 
part of the establishment so that black people could participate 
