accordingly the department is not at liberty to comment on the 
specifics of these programs 
the usda has had considerable experience in clandestine 
operations such as the decades of involement with the military in 
biological warfare projects during and after world war ii such 
us weapons were banned in 1969 
one twovolume report which was removed from the secret list in 
the late 1970s showed that usdas research in biological warfare 
was concentrated on the antipersonnel aspects of war 
there are also smaller programs in antianimal and anticrop 
bw biological warfare as outgrowths of the world war ii effort 
the report said the antianimal program was closely linked to 
the antipersonnel program since certain diseases produced effects 
in humans and animals and the scientific disciplines involved are 
identical or very similar 
according to the old reports the first limited bw retaliatory 
capability was achieved in 1951 when an anticrop bomb was 
developed tested and placed in production for the air force 
the first antianimal test was conducted in july 1951 but was 
discontinued three years later because it was concluded the program 
lacked military worth 
after sputtering a few times the anticrop program by 1969 
included three biological agents stem rust of wheat and rye and 
rice blast 
between 1951 and 1957 wheat stem rust spores and rye stem 
rust spores were produced from innoculated crops at planting sites 
located on government installations the report said the 
harvested spores were shipped to edgwwood arsenal md for 
classification drying and storage this operation was terminated 
in 1959 by the air force 
however that wasnt the end of the program to develop a wheat 
rust weapon between 1962 and 1969 rust spores were grown again at 
government sites with the material shipped to the rocky mountain 
arsenal for processing and storage 
all wheat rust spores were destroyed by february 1973 the 
report said rice blast inventories including final deliveries to 
fort detrick md were destroyed the previous year 
the roots of biological weaponry such as cocaeating 
caterpillars go back many years at least to world war i 
there is incontrovertible evidence for example that in 1915 
german agents inoculated horses and cattle leaving united states 
ports for shipment to the allies with diseaseproducing bacteria 
the report said 
in world war ii a formal stamp was put onto us efforts in the 
summer of 1942 when the war research service was approved by 
president franklin roosevelt 
appropriate liaison was maintained with the armed services 
the us public health service the department of agriculture and 
the department of interior the report said 
