<TEXT>
after months of debate and comment federal 
regulators have voted to bar people who violate major commodity 
futures exchange rules from serving on policy and rulemaking 
panels 
the commodity futures trading commission voted unanimously 
tuesday to approve a new regulation prohibiting rule violators from 
serving on disciplinary committees arbitration panels or governing 
boards of exchanges or futures associations 
the rule would bar violators for three years or for the length 
of any sanction imposed against them by an exchange whichever was 
longer it was first proposed by the cftc staff in september 
in other action the cftc approved an application by the new 
york mercantile exchange to trade futures contracts in natural gas 
the contract is designed to allow gas producers pipeline 
companies distributors and consumers to better determine prices 
and hedge against price fluctuations 
the new disciplinary rule is an outgrowth of congressional 
hearings into the fraud scandals at the nations two largest 
commodity futures exchanges last summer in chicago fortyeight 
people were indicted on charges linked to allegations of fradulent 
trading that surfaced in a twoyear undercover federal 
investigation 
a bill passed by the house and awaiting approval in the senate 
would require the cftc which oversees the futures industry to 
implement regulations barring major rule violators from sitting on 
the disciplinary committees of futures contract markets and futures 
associations 
the new rule will go into effect 30 days after it is published 
in the federal register 
spokesmen for the chicago mercantile exchange and the chicago 
board of trade said they now have stiffer rules governing their 
members 
the chicago mercantile exchanges andrew yemma said the cftc 
has already approved the rule change we proposed in mid1989 that 
bars anyone from serving on our board of governors or disciplinary 
committees for a period of five years if they have a major 
disciplinary history 
at the board of trade michael oconnell said the board of 
directors adopted a resolution in may reaffirming that it is and 
has been the policy of the bot that individual members with a 
history of significant trade practice sanctions will not be 
permitted to serve on the board of directors or exchange 
disciplinary committees 
according to the cftc rule people subject to the threeyear ban 
include those who violate major rules of selfregulated 
organizations such as futures exchanges or federal futures 
regulations people fined a total of more than 5000 in a single 
year for lesser violations also would be barred as well as those 
convicted of certain felonies including securities law violations 
embezzlement and fraud 
the new rule also requires selfregulating organizations to 
notify the cftc whenever it takes a disciplinary action that would 
disqualify an individual from serving on a committee or board 
the organizations also will be required to submit an annual list 
of people removed from committees under the rule 
</TEXT>
