the report was released tuesday by a group of advertisers media 
companies and ad agencies called the leadership council on 
advertising issues whose stated goal is to preserve and enhance 
the freedom to advertise 
our study shows that reduced advertising exacts social and 
economic penalties from the public said reginald brack the time 
warner inc executive who is cochairman of the group 
an author of the report said he hoped the findings would 
encourage discussion of social and economic costs whenever 
proposals to limit or tax advertising of tobacco beer wine and 
liquor are debated 
coauthor william lilley iii president of policy communications 
inc said policymakers often weigh only the social benefits at 
stake when discussing ad bans 
but critics called the findings unrealistic 
its just more scare tactics primarily said george hacker 
director for alcohol programs at the advocacy institute a 
washington dcbased group that often has aligned itself with 
antismoking efforts and campaigns to promote reduced use of 
alcohol 
it fails to take into account the fact that every day new 
products with advertising needs come on the market ready to spend 
tons of money to attract a consumer base the estimates of lost 
jobs and decimation of the industry are quite exaggerated he 
said 
hacker said the television industry recovered fairly quickly 
from the loss of ad revenue resulting from the 1971 ban on tv 
tobacco ads 
but lilley said media alternatives have grown since then and a 
ban on advertising legal products could markedly affect whether a 
wide range of television programming would be available without 
charge to viewers 
the report said beer and wine advertising for instance account 
for about 15 percent of the advertising on sports programs carried 
on the broadcast networks local tv stations and basic cable 
networks such as espn 
but if beer and wine advertising were banned the report said 
the decline in ad revenue would force those outlets to cut spending 
on sports programs 
the report estimated pay cable tv outlets that charge premiums 
over the basic rates or fees for each program would be the big 
winners boosting their sports programming by about 39 percent over 
current projections and paying for it by charging higher fees 
the lack of sports programs would reduce the audience for 
broadcast tv and the smaller audiences would mean less ad revenue 
and fewer resources for broadcasters to bid with for other 
programs the report said 
coverage of some sports such as boat racing might be dropped 
altogether it said 
the losers would be lowerincome consumers who could not afford 
paycable and those without access to cable tv who would be 
deprived of the full range of programs and information currently 
provided by broadcast tv the report said 
the report said a ban on beer and wine advertising would cost 
the broadcast television industry 4232 jobs or 29 percent of its 
work force by 1993 
a ban on tobacco advertising would put 165 magazines out of 
business trimming circulation by about 5 percent and eliminating 
4130 jobs the report said 
such general interest magazines as tv guide mccalls redbook 
and sports illustrated which the report said each get more than 
10 percent of their ad revenue from tobacco ads would feel the 
impact 
magazines with large circulation and low prices generally are 
least able to respond to losses of ad revenue the report said 
because cover price increases trigger sharp drops in circulation 
the report said lowerincome readers would be affected the most 
because they would be the most sensitive to higher magazine prices 
a tobacco advertising ban also would cost 7904 jobs in the 
newspaper business or 15 percent of the work force the report 
said 
the report said a ban on hard liquor advertising would force 84 
magazines out of business and cut magazine employment by 2100 
most severely affected would be mens magazines such as esquire 
and playboy which get about 10 percent of their ad revenue from 
liquor ads and minorityoriented magazines such as ebony and black 
enterprise which get 65 percent of their ad revenue from liquor 
ads the study said 
</TEXT>
