<TEXT>
britains merchandise trade deficit more than 
doubled in january to an unexpected 198 billion pounds or about 
33 billion at current exchange rates the government said 
wednesday 
the government blamed a drop in britains oil surplus and an 
unusually high level of imports of such items as diamonds for the 
widening gap between imports and exports 
the seasonally adjusted deficit compared with a deficit of 917 
million pounds in december the central statistical office said 
it said the current account deficit soared to 188 billion 
pounds from 817 million pounds the january current account deficit 
was the highest since september 1989 when it totaled 19 billion 
pounds 
excluding the unusual items would reduce the january current 
account figure by about 500 million pounds the office said 
the current account deficit equals the merchandise trade deficit 
plus invisibles trade 
invisibles cover services overseas investment earnings and 
official transfer payments and was estimated to be in surplus by 
100 million pound 
the january figures compare with market expectations of a 
merchandise trade deficit of 122 billion pounds and a current 
account deficit of 13 billion pounds 
exports totaled 86 billion pounds in january down from 87 
billion pounds in december imports totaled 106 billion pounds in 
january up from 96 billion pounds in december 
