<DOCNO> AP900228-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
you cant pay much attention to the financial 
news these days without seeing vivid images of the dangers of 
taking risks 
many junk bonds apparently are turning out to be true to 
their name the bank and savings and loan industries are littered 
with the casualties of illconsidered ventures 
supposedly sacrosanct real estate markets in places like the 
northeast have turned poisonous even the skyhigh japanese stock 
market seems not to be immune 
those who have suffered from these reversals arent attracting 
much sympathy the feeling among their fellows seems to be 
thats what comes of taking chances 
perhaps so but in the current climate of upheaval some 
students of the subject say the idea of risktaking itself may be 
getting a bad rap 
they argue that just about all business ventures like many 
other things in life are based on running risks 
in this view risk is pretty much a constant part of the 
natural order and even when it cannot be prevented or reduced it 
can be managed to minimize its harmful effects 
when mischief occurs it most often happens because people 
underestimated or just plain ignored the risks they were taking 
as john t reed a specialist in real estate investing put it 
gamblers take risks for the thrill of it investors take 
calculated risks because their calculations show they will be 
better off financially if they do 
the difference reed says in his newsletter real estate 
investors monthly can be illustrated through the simple device of 
a flip of a coin 
a gambler probablya would take an evenmoney bet that a given 
coin flip would turn up heads devotees of lotteries and other 
longshot propositions might even stake small amounts on the chance 
that the coin would land on its edge 
but wise investors would look for some edge in their favor 
before they put their money up on a 5050 proposition like a coin 
flip for example they might demand a payoff of 11 for each 10 
chance they took 
in addition to knowing their statistical chances of success 
investors like to know as precisely as possible the expected value 
of winning and the penalty paid for losing 
on top of that they inquire into the worst possible outcomes 
that could befall them in order to gauge their exposure even to 
freakish damage 
for people who dont patronize casinos what use is all this 
well it turns out there is much more to riskmanagement in the 
world than eschewing gambling 
customers of insurance companies for example merely buy the 
right to transfer a risk they face to an institution that is 
willing to assume it for a price that is usually profitable 
likewise investing of all kinds involves at least an estimate 
of risk the aggressive individual may opt for some vehicle 
with a speculative reputation the conservative investor sticks 
with supposed safety 
but when the information used to make the calculation is suspect 
or not fully understood reed observes to discuss the issue in 
terms of optimism vs conservatism is to descend to mere 
namecalling 
the question is not who is optimistic or who is conservative 
the question is who is right 
either you have the data to calculate your risks or you dont 
inadequate data combined with optimism is still inadequate data 
indeed that combination is more dangerous than inadequate data 
alone 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

