<TEXT>
recent upheavals in japans capital markets may put 
a financial squeeze on japanese industry and slow economic growth 
analysts say but few believe a recession will result 
economic conditions are still strong said hiroshi kadota of 
the japan federation of economic organizations financial affairs 
bureau investment is expanding the capital markets are 
returning to a normal trend 
japanese industry for years has been able to raise capital for 
growth at relatively little cost but its fabled markets have shown 
signs of sputtering lately 
the tokyo stock exchange where sony corp for example raised 
27 billion earlier this month to help finance its overseas 
investments has gyrated wildly this year after reaching record 
highs at the close of 1989 the exchanges key index declined by 
some 14 percent before rebounding tuesday and wednesday 
interest rates have been rising since last summer when the bank 
of japan began battling inflation by raising its discount rate 
the interest it charges for loans to commercial banks to 425 
percent from 25 percent anticipation of a further increase has 
send bond prices plummeting in tandem with stock prices increasing 
corporate borrowing costs 
many analysts regard these developments as corrections in an 
overheated capital market rather than a vote of no confidence in 
the underlying economy 
adrian tschoegl an economist with sbci securities asia said 
the fall in the tokyo market is a bit like the new york crash of 
87 everyone cried recession then but nothing much happened 
the tokyo market is coming down from an overheated level the 
effect is going to be very slight 
nevertheless with interest rates up and the stock market down 
some japanese companies apparently are shelving plans to raise 
equity capital in the near future and are turning to their own 
reserves to fuel growth 
several issues were involved in have been pulled back 
tschoegl said 
as much as 68 billion worth of convertible bonds warrants and 
shares were scheduled to come on to the market by the end of march 
several brokers said many of these issues will be deferred they 
said 
equity financing is one of the most important vehicles to 
raise funds for japanese corporations obviously they do not want 
to go ahead now if they believe theyre going to hurt their 
longterm financing said yutaka nakai an analyst with daiwa 
securities co they can be flexible about when to raise funds 
large japanese corporations are able to weather rough sailing in 
the capital markets said kadota because they have vast reserves 
of liquidity he said a poll of business leaders conducted this 
month by his organization found confidence in continued growth was 
high 
