<TEXT>
the name of the kansas city star will 
live on when the storied 110yearold afternoon paper where young 
ernest hemingway worked as a reporter merges thursday with its 
morning partner the kansas city times 
many other things will go the stars afternoon publishing 
time its layout and typeface some call it the end of an era 
but editor joe mcguff sees just another stage in the newspapers 
colorful history which began in 1880 in a rough but booming river 
town and includes years when political boss tom pendergast ruled 
the citys voting booths and the papers president roy roberts 
helped persuade dwight eisenhower hed be a good president 
the stars course has included pulitzers corporate buyouts and 
growing competition with tv the star and times have won seven 
pulitzers including a joint award for their investigation into the 
1981 hyatt regency skywalk collapse that killed 114 people 
like hundreds of afternoon papers the star has faced declining 
readership its circulation dropped by 100000 in the 80s and 
stood at 165000 in september the times circulation is 270000 
the stars sunday readership is 416000 
its inevitable and that takes away some of the sting said 
george r burg who started on the desk in 1948 moved up to 
managing editor and now directs philanthropic activities as 
assistant to the publisher people just dont read afternoon 
papers anymore 
william rockhill nelson and samuel e morss started the kansas 
city evening star on sept 18 1880 a debut with a circulation of 
3000 the fourpage paper cost 2 cents nelson bought out his 
partner the next year 
by 1892 circulation was 50000 in 1901 nelson purchased the 
33yearold times which even at the turn of the century was still 
a diehard sympathizer of the confederate cause the words the 
morning kansas city star appeared as a subhead on its masthead 
until 1977 
hemingway joined the star in 1917 covering the train station a 
hospital and police precinct before leaving seven months later to 
join an ambulance unit in italy 
when nelson died in 1915 his will stipulated the paper should 
go to his wife and daughter and then be sold after their deaths 
employees led by nelsons soninlaw irwin kirkwood submitted the 
winning bid in 1926 and established the employee ownership that 
would stand for five decades 
the newspaper earned a reputation as a crusader when it turned 
against pendergast in the mid1930s and the political boss fell 
from power all the way to a prison cell for tax evasion 
in the mid20th century the newspapers president was roberts 
who sat at his desk in the newsroom talking to the republican rich 
and powerful on the phone he persuaded one friend eisenhower to 
run for president 
in 1977 capital cities communications based in new york 
bought the paper for 125 million making millionaires of a few 
stockholders 
they made a lot of changes that resulted in firings and forced 
retirements said joe henderson the papers longtime federal 
court reporter who is retiring it was a bitter time but those 
who survived are certainly a lot better off in salary and fringe 
benefits i think than under the old star 
the merger wont result in any layoffs for the 300 newsroom 
employees 
the times remained in the stars shadow for years times 
reporters for example identified themselves as star reporters 
when doing interviews 
otherwise no one would have known who they were said burg 
but as the stars circulation dropped over the years the times 
got more important its circulation bypassed the stars in 1965 
after the 1977 sale editors placed the two news staffs in 
direct competition for the first time in an effort to improve 
reporting advertising and production staffs worked for both papers 
despite the attempt at direct competition the star in the last 
decade became known for its features while the times concentrated 
on national international and regional news 
now employees and readers await thursday mornings newspapers 
and morning newspapers thereafter 
one lady told me shell have to read half the paper in the 
morning burg said and save the other half for afternoon 
