<TEXT>
a year ago the eastern airlines terminal at 
sprawling atlanta airport resembled a ghost town shut down by 
angry pickets in what has become one of the longest strikes in 
commercial aviation history 
today the strikers have dwindled to bitter holdouts of the 
machinists union and the terminal pulsates with passengers 
digested and disgorged by eastern jetliners 
but beyond the unmarked doors down corridors to offices and 
employee lounges a revolution is under way eastern is 
transforming with youthful blood about the only things unchanged 
are the name and the bluesilver logo 
once heavily dependent on florida tourism and latin travel 
eastern is redirecting its reach toward business passengers the 
airlines headquarters may be in miami but the most important 
operation is now in atlantas hartsfield international one of the 
worlds busiest airports 
many employees are cherubfaced new hires some flight 
attendants look barely out of their teens and a number of pilots 
are in their 30s they work for less money than their prestrike 
counterparts and harbor none of the labor bitterness that helped 
drag eastern down for years 
to passengers the new eastern not only looks rejuvenated 
but its almost evangelical new employees bubble with conviction 
that theyre on the ground floor of something big 
strikescarred veterans say theres less bureaucratic bickering 
within the airline now many say theyre pulling together like a 
team helped partly by companypaid counseling aimed at overcoming 
the bitterness caused by the strike 
nonetheless it remains unclear whether the new eastern 
which lost 8523 million last year can survive the unions have 
been humbled but the airline has reasserted itself just as the 
economy seems to be weakening leaving even the strongest airlines 
vulnerable 
we face a much more sinister challenge now said james 
ashlock an eastern spokesman in atlanta who is an unofficial 
historian of the airline weve got to make it 
like an aging jet eastern has been stripped and overhauled by 
owner frank lorenzo with the sanction of a federal bankruptcy 
judge the airline filed for protection from creditors soon after 
the strike began and has since sold 8598 million in assets the 
workforce has been cut to about 20000 vs 28000 before the 
walkout 
to easterns management however the airline hasnt been gutted 
as union leaders claim but rejiggered reshaped and rebuilt 
nobodys ever built an airline like this this fast said 
eastern vice president harold holt highestranking manager in 
atlanta he said expanding the atlanta operation during the strike 
was one of the more stressful tasks of his 40 years with the 
company 
you either remain calm or go nuts he said its been 
probably the worst period in my career and also the best 
for holt a softspoken atlanta native that period began march 
4 1989 when eastern pilots and flight attendants walked out in 
solidarity with the machinists and grounded all flights 
holt and his colleagues scrambled to train replacement workers 
to gradually rebuild the flight schedule which went from 295 a day 
to zero overnight in atlanta alone and created havoc in the early 
days of the strike the managers hauled bags and cleaned planes 
while management pilots took over the cockpits 
as the strike progressed the atlanta schedule was increased to 
80 flights a day in july 160 in august and 262 in september 
eastern now has about 270 daily departures from atlanta and its 
target is 315 by mid to late 1990 
nearly a third of easterns workforce is based in atlanta 
including about 1000 pilots 1400 flight attendants 750 
mechanics and maintenance workers 1000 baggage handlers and 1000 
ticket agents cleaners and other workers 
atlantas going to be between 40 and 50 percent of eastern 
airlines holt said 
systemwide the new eastern operates about 800 flights a day 
to 86 cities that will be cut sharply if the federal government 
approves easterns agreement to sell its latin american routes and 
other assets to american airlines for 471 million 
the sale of those routes is a required condition for final 
approval of a new reorganization agreement between eastern and its 
major creditors 
lorenzo recently pulled easterns healthier sister carrier 
continental airlines into the bankruptcy fray in order to gain 
acceptance from the big creditors for its reorganization plan 
continental like eastern a subsidiary of lorenzos texas air 
corp would be required to make some payments to easterns 
creditors under the new plan 
if the sale to american proceeds the importance to eastern of 
miami its latin american hub will diminish still further 
atlanta the business center of the south will become easterns 
key market 
it is in this city that uppity eastern is going nosetonose 
against staid delta air lines the nations fourthlargest carrier 
and a dominant economic force in atlanta its home base 
eastern employees jokingly call an outdoor area of hartsfield 
separating the two airlines facilities the demilitarized zone 
they refer to delta as the big bear across the terminal 
as miamis role in easterns game plan shrinks there is even 
speculation that eastern could sell its maintenance base there and 
move more operations to atlanta this citys civic and business 
leaders have been pressing eastern to transfer everything here 
holt said 
regardless of where eastern concentrates its business there is 
little doubt that the rancorous workermanagement relationship of 
the prestrike years has eased 
