<TEXT>
treasury undersecretary david mulford said 
wednesday that officials of the seven largest industrial countries 
met in london this week but he refused to confirm a report that 
japan had requested help in stabilizing the value of the japanese 
currency 
i cant answer questions about current exchange rates 
mulford told reporters after an appearance before a congressional 
panel he said he attended the tuesday meeting 
mulford was asked about a report by a japanese news organization 
that officials in that country had asked other major industrial 
countries to keep the yen from falling further 
the kyodo news service quoting a finance ministry source said 
japan made the request at a meeting of deputy finance minsters from 
the industrial countries which are known as the group of seven 
the seven governments the united states japan west germany 
britain france italy and canada often work together to buy and 
sell currencies on the open market to influence their price 
the yen has been declining rapidly against the dollar in recent 
weeks threatening to ignite inflation in japan a decline in the 
yen also risks worsening the us trade deficit by making american 
goods more expensive and japanese goods cheaper 
the dollar gained against the yen wednesday closing at 14908 
yen in new york compared with 14873 yen on tuesday 
mulford confirmed for reporters that he had attended a g7 
deputies meeting in london on tuesday other sources had said the 
session was with officials at mulfords level and not at the 
ministerial level although treasury secretary nicholas brady was 
also in london tuesday 
while refusing to confirm that stabilizing the japanese yen was 
on the agenda mulford said the group did discuss establishment of 
a european bank for reconstruction and development to help foster 
emerging democracies in eastern europe 
he said he hoped that the bank could begin operating by the end 
of this year but that there was no assurance that this timetable 
could be met 
at wednesdays hearing of a house banking committee task force 
mulford said the g7 countries have been successfully coordinating 
their domestic policies to foster global prosperity 
mulford told the lawmakers he could not make a statement on the 
controversial issue of whether the soviet union should be allowed 
to borrow from the new bank 
were still in the process of learning from what weve 
heard he said 
the bush administration had been reported earlier as opposing 
loans from the bank to the soviet union while other donor 
governments wanted to permit them 
mulford said the administration is anxious to set up special 
standards for loans that are not required by other development 
banks requirements that borrowers move toward democracy 
pluralism free political parties elections the rule of law 
human rights and open marketbased economies 
he said the us government wants to join the bank and its first 
concern is how to finance the transition from communism to 
economies based on markets he suggested that if the bank lends 
chiefly to governments it may promote the existing situation rather 
than contribute to changing it 
