<TEXT>
regardless of whether exxon corp ever goes to 
trial on criminal charges the oil giants indictment in connection 
with its alaska oil spill could cause exxons disasterrelated 
expenses to snowball beyond the 2 billion it already has spent 
experts said wednesday 
dan riesel an environmental attorney with the law firm sive 
paget amp riesel said a number of outcomes are possible in the exxon 
case including an eventual dismissal of the charges 
in the event of a conviction or a plea bargain however 
criminal proceedings against exxon could benefit those who have 
filed civil lawsuits and swell exxons financial burden said 
riesel a former environmental prosecutor for the us attorneys 
office in new york 
if exxon is forced to articulate what it did in a plea bargain 
process it makes life awfully simple for private plaintiffs and 
very difficult for exxon riesel said those are admissions and 
admissions can be used in another proceeding to prove liability 
a federal grand jury in alaska handed up a fivecount criminal 
indictment against exxon on tuesday for counts stemming from the 
oil spill by the tanker exxon valdez after it hit a reef last march 
24 in alaskas prince william sound the spill of 11 million 
gallons of oil soiled over 1000 miles of coastline and killed 
thousands of fish birds and other animals 
more than 160 civil lawsuits are pending against exxon by the 
state of alaska environmentalists and private individuals for 
unspecified damages 
the criminal outcome also could result in fines totaling twice 
the loss to the victim in this case what it cost to restore the 
environment to its condition prior to the spill riesel said 
if measured by the cost of rebuilding the ecosystem then 
were talking an astronomical sum billions he said 
exxon chairman lawrence rawl said tuesday that exxon already has 
spent more than 2 billion in cleanup costs and has paid out more 
than 180 million to 13000 fishermen and other claimants 
the company took 168 billion in charges against 1989 earnings 
to cover what it said was both current and estimated future costs 
for cleanup environmental and legal expenses 
nevertheless tuesdays indictment raised uncertainty about what 
exxons final responsibility would be in the spill 
justice department officials said the indictment could result in 
penalties of 700 million or more but analysts said actual 
financial impact to the oil giant remained too uncertain to 
quantify because exxon failed to reach a settlement over possible 
criminal charges 
exxon reportedly had been negotiating a plea agreement with the 
justice department that would have involved the creation of a 500 
million environmental restoration fund 
i doubt it will cost more than what exxon has already put 
out said joseph v battipaglia equities analyst with gruntal 
investment research he said however its not altogether clear 
to what extent there will be extraordinary expenses arising from 
the indictment 
the absence of a plea bargain only keeps the uncertainty 
said frank p knuettel analyst for prudential bache securities inc 
knuettel and other analysts say the companys enormous size 
insulates it from the financial impact of the spill 
exxon is wealthier than a hundred countries in the un 
said knuettel 
exxons stock dropped 137 to 47 on the new york stock 
exchange in what analysts called a temporary kneejerk 
reaction to the indictment which was announced after the market 
closed tuesday the stock generally was expected to improve in 1990 
battipaglia noted the stock remained above the 45 range in 
which it was trading before the spill exxon stock has been 
relatively flat since the spill 
another uncertainty is the outcome of the trial in alaska of 
joseph hazelwood former captain of the exxon valdez at the time of 
the spill 
hazelwood charged with a felony criminal mischief and three 
misdemeanors is the only person charged criminally in the tanker 
grounding 
analysts said the amount of damages sought in civil lawsuits 
likely would climb if hazelwood is convicted many of the lawsuits 
do not yet specify a damage amount 
