a leading credit rating agency warned 
wednesay that harcourt brace jovanovich inc may have to sell more 
assets to meet payments coming due in late 1992 on its 16 billion 
debt 
the warning from moodys investors service inc came as harcourt 
reported that a big gain on the sale of its theme parks helped the 
publishing and insurance concern earn 3166 million in the fourth 
quarter compared with a loss of 539 million during same period a 
year ago 
moodys said that despite the sale of the theme parks and 
subsequent repayment of bank debt harcourts cash flow from its 
publishing and insurance properties will provide only narrow 
coverage of anticipated cash interest charges and capital 
expenditures over the near term 
as a result moodys also lowered its ratings on harcourts debt 
the ratings agency said that the requirement that harcourt must 
pay cash interest and dividends in late 1992 and 1993 is likely 
to necessitate further asset sales andor debt restructuring 
it downgraded harcourts senior debt rating to b3 from b1 and 
ratings on other grades of debt were also reduced the companys 
debt had been assigned a speculative grade before the action and 
the reductions indicate the agency feels chances for timely debt 
repayment have grown riskier 
the debt rating is one of the factors that are considered in 
valuing a companys securities and a ratings reduction often 
causes a decline in the market price of a companys bonds 
two calls were placed to harcourt for comment on moodys action 
but they were not immediately returned 
harcourt amassed a huge debt nearly three years ago when it 
underwent a massive restructuring in an effort to avoid a hostile 
takeover by british publisher robert maxwell 
in the fourth quarter harcourt said its earnings per share 
amounted to 422 in contrast to a loss of 108 per share a year 
earlier 
fourthquarter revenue slipped 07 percent to 3017 million 
from 3038 million a year earlier 
the company closed the sale of its six theme parks to 
anheuserbusch cos for 11 billion in the quarter it reported a 
gain on disposal of assets of 309 million in the quarter 
it reported net income from continuing operations of 195 
million for the quarter in contrast to a loss from continuing 
operations of 547 million 
for the year harcourt said it earned 721 million or 17 cents 
a share in contrast to a loss of 534 million or 203 a share 
a year earlier 
revenue for the year rose 55 percent to 134 billion from 
127 billion a year earlier 
