<DOCNO> AP900228-0289 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a senate committee approved legislation 
wednesday aimed at providing greater protection of pension payments 
when companies terminate retirement plans to capture their surplus 
assets 
the legislation by sens howard metzenbaum dohio and nancy 
kassebaum rkan would impose new standards on pension fund 
administrators in deciding whether to terminate retirement plans 
this bill will stop employers from using their workers 
pension plans as corporate piggybanks metzenbaum said in a 
statement after the senate labor and human resources committee 
approved the bill on a 115 vote 
kassebaum and sen james jeffords rvt joined with the 
panels democratic majority in voting to send the bill to the floor 
surplus pension assets have become a popular target for 
corporate raiders who acquire a company and quickly end socalled 
defined benefit retirement programs to take any excess cash 
defined benefit programs are administered by trustees or the 
employer and promise a certain benefit on retirement socalled 
defined contribution plans where the company contributes to an 
employees account generally are not at issue because the employe 
owns the funds and there is no surplus cash when it comes time to 
retire the money is turned over the employee or buys an annuity 
in general the legislation would allow a company to strip out 
surplus pension assets only if is determined to be in the best 
interests of workers and retirees 
the bill requires the company to consider specific issues in 
making that determination including whether costofliving 
benefits would be provided to retirees and whether an adequate 
financial cushion can be maintained in any replacement retirement 
plan 
metzenbaum has maintained that at least a portion of surplus 
pension assets should be set aside for costofliving adjustments 
in retirement benefits the legislation does not require colas but 
makes it more likely they would be provided according to 
supporters of the measure 
the pension benefit guaranty corp must approve pension fund 
terminations however critics complain that existing law doesnt 
adequately take into account whether pension beneficiaries will be 
better or worse off if a corporation takes back excess money from 
retirement plans 
workers who have been promised pensions should be assured 
those promises will be fulfilled and that their interests will take 
first place in these situations kassebaum said 
excess cash can arise in definedbenefit plans in several ways 
one common way is the upward revision of estimates of what plan 
assets can earn the higher the estimates the less cash is needed 
now to meet future obligations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

