<TEXT>
chrysler corp said its ready to sell its 1 
billion stillunfinished technical center and then lease it back 
gaining 800 million in badly needed cash along the way 
the move announced tuesday is seen as a way for the financially 
struggling no 3 automaker to raise the money it needs to finance a 
costcutting program that includes thousands of whitecollar early 
retirements 
it looks to me like the smartest way to do it at the moment 
said auto analyst charles brady of oppenheimer amp co in new york 
chrysler on monday filed papers with the securities and exchange 
commission in washington seeking permission to sell and lease back 
its chrysler technology center in auburn hills about 25 miles 
north of detroit 
chrysler spokesman tom houston said tuesday the company would 
sell the center to the auburn hills trust which in turn would 
offer certificates to raise 800 million for chrysler 
the trust then would lease the center to the auburn hills trust 
services property management company which would collect lease 
payments from chrysler to repay the 800 million by 2020 
there are two basic advantages houston said we can raise 
more money than we could with a conventional mortgage and we get 
800 million for use by the company thats not tied up in the 
center 
the money he said will go into chryslers general operating 
coffers 
the salelease arrangement is the latest in a series of moves 
chrysler has made to get rid of nonautomotive businesses and raise 
cash 
last september chrysler sold nearly half of its stake in 
mitsubishi motors corp of japan and made about 310 million after 
taxes earlier this month it sold its gulfstream aerospace corp 
subsidiary for 825 million 
the company has been waging a costcutting program to chisel 
about 15 billion from its 26 billion annual budget by the end of 
the year 
that program includes trimming more than 10 percent of the 
whitecollar work force through attrition or early retirement 
which costs money 
chrysler reported that it lost 664 million in the fourth 
quarter of 1989 including 577 million in writeoffs for two car 
assembly plants the company is closing this year it was the 
automakers first quarterly loss since 1982 
chrysler and state government officials broke ground for the 
25millionsquarefoot complex in october 1986 it originally was 
targeted to be completed this year and house 5000 employees 
houston said the completion date now is 1993 and the center will 
house 7000 workers most of whom now work at the companys 
highland park headquarters 
</TEXT>
