<TEXT>
seabrook nuclear power plant proponents 
and opponents rarely agree but both say the regulatory process 
leading up to thursdays expected licensing of the plant 14 years 
after groundbreaking has been ridiculous 
both sides expect the nuclear regulatory commission to license 
the 65 billion plant owned by a dozen utilities but opponents 
promised legal action to keep it idle 
i never thought it would take this long said former gov 
meldrim thomson a seabrook supporter who served during 197379 
if any human being could dream up anything worse they would 
have to work at it thomson said weve been told over and over 
again that weve built the best and safest plant thats ever been 
built its ridiculous that it hasnt been licensed 
veteran antiseabrook protester paul gunter first arrested at 
the plant in 1976 is equally critical but from the opposite 
viewpoint 
the regulatory process has been in the hands of a promotional 
agency rather than a regulatory agency he said the nrc has 
basically pulled seabrook into operation even though it cant meet 
the law and protect human safety 
dianne dunfey another veteran protester was released from jail 
last week after serving a fiveday term for refusing to pay a fine 
following a sitin at gov judd greggs office she called the nrc 
one of the most disreputable of all government agencies 
it has ignored public input said dunfey who teaches in 
seabrook it either discarded or amended all of its own 
regulations anytime seabrook couldnt meet one 
asked why the licensing procedure had taken as long as it did 
nrc spokesman john kopeck in washington said there was a legal 
process that it had to go through there were a lot of steps that 
had to be taken 
if promised court appeals dont succeed seabrook would go 
through a threemonth buildup to fullpower operation 
the main point in the way of licensing was the federal 
requirement for evacuation plans for communities within 10 miles of 
the plant including six in massachusetts 
opponents say the area surrounding the plant about two miles 
from popular hampton beach and 40 miles north of boston is too 
densely populated to be evacuated safely in an emergency 
the regulatory process at the nrc is largely a charade sen 
gordon humphrey rnh said in a telephone interview wednesday 
they have brushed aside concerns about evacuation anybody whos 
been in a traffic jam near the plant during the summer knows that 
in a panic situation evacuation would be impossible 
seabrook proponents including former gov john sununu now 
white house chief of staff say the plans will work sununu 
declined to comment on the plant this week but as governor he was 
a vocal supporter 
it may be a surprise but we run the analogy of an 
evacuation experiment 730 each summer day sununu said during 
a 1983 debate at 730 that beach is crowded and at 11 at 
night that beach is empty 
while environmental groups and the massachusetts attorney 
general fought the evacuation plans the grassroots clamshell 
alliance staged antiseabrook demonstrations that made the plant a 
national focus of the antinuclear movement in the 1970s and 80s 
the last major seabrook demonstration was in october when 475 
people were arrested after scaling the fences 
a few opponents began vigils tuesday at the statehouse and 
outside seabrook a larger demonstration was to follow the 
licensing vote 
seabrooks path toward licensing has been a rocky one 
seabrooks lead owner public service co of new hampshire filed 
for a permit to build twin 1150megawatt reactors in 1973 the 
first was to operate commercially in 1979 the second in 1981 
total cost was estimated at 973 million 
the nrc approved the permit in 1976 but it was suspended three 
times in the late 1970s in disputes over radioactive waste and 
tunnels for cooling water 
the first reactor was finished in the mid1986 at a cost of 43 
billion the second 25 percent complete was scrapped that year 
since then financing and operating costs have boosted the cost by 
50 million a month bringing the total by thursday to 65 billion 
public service filed for bankruptcy in january 1988 under the 
burden of its seabrook debt 
</TEXT>
